description: Celebrated at international festivals, Nadav Lapid's films have provoked controversy in his home country. His latest work, the acerbic 'Yes,' explores the aftermath of October 7 and sharply criticizes a society consumed by vengeance and nationalism.

description: For the first time since 2023, labor unions have called for protests across all sectors, from schools to transport, in opposition to austerity measures in the 2026 budget plan which the new prime minister has not ruled out.

headline: Kvaratskhelia stunner helps holders PSG to winning Champions League start
description: Paris Saint-Germain, which won 4-0 against Atalanta on Wednesday, hardly had any off-season break after the last campaign, which stretched over 65 games and 11 months. The French Club's victory comes after losing star forwards Ousmane Dembélé and Désiré Doué for several weeks to injuries.

headline: El Salvador: From 'Surf City' beaches to overflowing prisons – the two sides of the Bukele model
description: President Nayib Bukele has propelled El Salvador to the top of the world ranking for incarceration rate, with nearly 1.7% of the population behind bars. At the same time, the Central American state has welcomed 3.5 million tourists, far outpacing Costa Rica.

headline: Who is Gabriel Zucman, billionaires' nightmare?
description: Since Sébastien Lecornu's appointment as prime minister, Gabriel Zucman's name has been everywhere in French media. The economist's proposal for a 2% wealth tax on the ultra-rich has returned to the forefront of public debate.

headline: An abbey in southern France rescued by contemporary art
description: 'Strange places for an exhibition' (6/6). Le Monde explores six art centers set up in unusual locations. Today: a magnificent Cistercian abbey rescued from ruin by Geneviève Bonnefoi and Pierre Brache.

headline: The Paris district where Parisians are priced out
description: In 50 years, the 8th arrondissement of the French capital, home to the Champs-Elysées and the 'Golden Triangle,' has lost nearly half its population. The mass acquisition of real estate by ultra-wealthy foreigners has driven locals out.
